# Overview

This project focuses on building a custom AWS Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) from scratch to understand cloud networking fundamentals, including subnetting, routing, and secure access to public and private resources.

⸻

# What I Built
	•	A custom VPC with a /16 CIDR block
	•	One public subnet and one private subnet with non-overlapping CIDRs
	•	An Internet Gateway (IGW) for public internet access
	•	A NAT Gateway for private subnet outbound access
	•	Separate route tables for public and private traffic
	•	Public, private, and bastion EC2 instances with least-privilege access

⸻

# Network Design
	•	VPC CIDR: 10.0.0.0/16
	•	Public Subnet: 10.0.0.0/20
	•	Private Subnet: 10.0.16.0/20

The public subnet is used for internet-facing resources, while the private subnet is isolated from direct internet access.

⸻

# Internet Access & Routing
	•	An Internet Gateway was attached to the VPC to allow public subnet resources to communicate with the internet.
	•	A NAT Gateway was deployed in the public subnet to enable outbound internet access for private subnet resources.
	•	Two route tables were created:
	•	Public route table:
	•	0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway
	•	Private route table:
	•	0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway
	•	Each subnet was explicitly associated with the correct route table to enforce traffic flow.

⸻

# Compute & Access
	•	Public EC2 instance
	•	Public IP enabled
	•	Security group allows SSH and HTTP only from my IP
	•	Private EC2 instance
	•	No public IP
	•	Security group allows SSH only from a trusted internal source
	•	Bastion Host
	•	Publicly accessible EC2 instance
	•	Used as a secure entry point to access private instances

Security groups were configured using security group references rather than CIDR ranges to restrict internal access.

⸻

# Lessons Learned
	•	Public and private access in AWS is enforced through routing, not just subnet naming.
	•	NAT Gateways are required for private instances to access the internet securely.
	•	Bastion hosts provide a controlled way to manage private resources without exposing them publicly.
	•	Careful route table association is critical to prevent unintended internet exposure.

⸻

# Outcome

This assignment established a solid foundation in AWS networking concepts and directly informed later projects involving load balancers, private compute, and multi-tier architectures.


# Braindump of what I did:

Created the VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) called assignment-1-VPC (10.0.0.0/16)

created two subnets separately, one public and one private.
public subnet was given 10.0.0.0/20 and private was given 10.0.16.0/20

Created an Internet Gateway very easily and then clicked actions to attach it to the VPC

Created a NAT Gateway though it ended up in a failed state and i had to delete it and recreate it after i was doing the route tables
Created new NAT Gateway and it was good and i connected it to route table

For the route tables i made two tables, public and private.
On the public table i associated the public subnet and edited the routes to include a second route (destination 0.0.0.0/0 and target IGW i created)
for the private route table i associated the private subnet and edited the routes to include a second route (destination 0.0.0.0/0 and target NATGW-2)

Next step was creating the instances
Made a public EC2 instance with public IP enabled and security group only allow ssh and http from my IP
Made a private EC2 instance with public IP disabled and security group only allow ssh from public EC2 instance, Which meant i inputted Security group ID as source when selecting custom source
I also created a third instance which had public IP enabled and could ssh from anywhere - This is the bastion host in order to access the private EC2 instance
